template<class T >
js_proxy_t* js_get_or_create_proxy ( JSContext *  cx,
T *  native_obj 
)

you don't need to manage the returned pointer. The returned pointer should be deleted using JS_REMOVE_PROXY. Most of the time you do that in the C++ destructor.

template<class T >
js_type_class_t* js_get_type_from_native ( T *  native_obj)

You don't need to manage the returned pointer. They live for the whole life of the app.
